defaultDo local bodies (including local authorities, local enterprise partnerships, passenger transport executives, integrated transport 
defaultauthorities and local transport boards) have the capacity to assess, 
defaultprioritise
default and deliver local transport schemes? What would the optimum delivery body look like?
defaultI take local to mean exactly that - within a locality such as a town or borough, or a disti
defaultnct and separate rural area.   The great weakness of the current system is that local government at the County level has been subjected to cutbacks and seemingly constant 
defaultrationalisations
default (i.e. redundancies and 
defaultreorganisations
default).   This has created disconti
defaultnuity and a certain amount of corporate paralysis.   There seems to be no overarching coherent policy that requires urgency to deliver it.   For example - there is evidence that S106 money is held up by bureaucracy.   There are no longer budgets allocated 
defaultto specific means of transport which means that - for example, cycle schemes that might deliver real benefit don't get 
defaultrecognised
default as part of a core transport policy - more as a fringe and 
defaultmarginalised
default form of transport; although the talk in public is diffe
defaultrent.   The CLC process is incapable of dealing with the volume that should go through its hands.   Consequently, those schemes that are easy to understand and 
defaultquickly 
defaultdecide on - get the vote.
default&#xa0;
defaultApart from benefitting from some isolated serendipitous schem
defaultes, West Sussex County Council has not made any serious attempt to implement its 
defaultLocal Plan Transport Plan 3
default (LTP3) 
defaultand has, similarly, made no attempt to replace it with anything else.
default&#xa0;
default This, therefore, poses the question ‘what is the point of all of the 
defaulteffort put in to these plans if the Council has no mechanism to support it or implementing it?’
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultTo answer the question - 
defaultlocal bodies do not have the capacity to assess, 
defaultprioritise
default and deliver local transport schemes.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe optimum delivery body is one th
defaultat considers and values the economic, health and 
defaultsocial benefits of sustainable transport, and incorporates those benefits into an integrated policy with a 'golden thread' running through transport, health, social and economic development policies.   It sh
defaultould consult with, and take 'on the ground' information from, those who know the locality.   Those consulted should be involved in the roll out of schemes.  
default&#xa0;
defaultLocal bodies (district and borough councils) are inconsistent in their approach to sustainable tr
defaultansport. Decisions made by the county council in allocating funding to sustainable transport are not backed-up by, and are even contradicted by, decisions of Council Local Committees. The co-ordination of cycle schemes at county council level has been aban
defaultdoned with the abolition of the West Sussex County Council Cycling Officer and although there is someone doing his best to work with local cycle and sustainable transport groups, the fact is that he has another full time job that takes all his time.
