defaultHow clear are the lines of accountability for
default local decision making on transport expenditure?
defaultThe answer is that they are unclear to most.  But you must be more precise about what is meant by 'clear'.  It's an absolute term and when you factor in the implied 'clear to whom', then it's obvious that it
default might be 100% clear to some 
default- 
defaultbut 
defaultunhelpfully 
defaultopaque to others.  
defaultSo - please be 
defaultless ambiguous
default.   But 
default- 
defaultof greater importance is whether local decision making is 
defaultappropriate, relevant and worthwhile
default.   For example, it could be crystal clear but hopeless
default,
default 
defaultinappropriate, irrelevant and worthless. 
default&#xa0;
defaultIt is 
defaultabsolutely 
defaultnot clear where accountability sits for the cycling elements of the West Sussex 
defaultCounty Council 
defaultLocal Transport Plan 3 
default(LTP3) - 
defaultand more specifically for cycling safety. 
default  
defaultIs it still a central res
defaultponsibility of the county council as the Highways Authority, or the County Local Committees, who control the key funding streams
default; funding streams
default that could be used to implement cycle schemes and improve cycling safety?
